If the greatest common divisor (GCD) of \( H_n \) and \( L_n \) is greater than 1, then \( k_n \) will be less than \( L_n \). - This happens when \( H_n \) can be simplified by dividing both the numerator and the denominator by a common factor greater than 1. 2. **Even Numbers**: - For even \( n \geq 6 \), the LCM \( L_n \) includes all prime factors up to \( n \), making it more likely that \( k_n \) will be less than \( L_n \). - For odd \( n \), especially \( n = 2 \) and \( n = 4 \), \( k_n \) equals \( L_n \), so they are excluded. 3. **Counting Valid \( n \)**: - From \( n = 6 \) to \( n = 22 \) (even numbers only), we have 8 valid values of \( n \). ### Conclusion: The number of integers \( n \) between 1 and 22 where \( k_n < L_n \) is **8**.
